<dl id="n12012a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12012a">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12012a"> 12(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> semantic ~ <small>Red</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n12012a"><li>FW 173.32 </li><li><a href="../../flex/g/lexg.htm#n12012a">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/g/l39g.htm#n12012a">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n12012a">MS BL 47474-25v</ms> </li><li>JJA 47:404 <a name="gd3" href="../../FF/fdra/gda.htm#gd3">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/g/gd3.htm#n12012a">Draft: I.7&sect;1.3</a>/2.3</li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">Mais la vraie question n&apos;&eacute;tait pas l&agrave;: vaut-il mieux, oui ou non, conna&icirc;tre notre langue, vocabulaire, syntaxe, s&eacute;mantique m&ecirc;me, de l&apos;int&eacute;rieur, &agrave; l&apos;aide du latin, et en remontant sans cesse &agrave; ce pass&eacute; t&eacute;n&eacute;breux? L&apos;imprudent auteur avait os&eacute; affirmer que Racine et Montaigne sont assur&eacute;ment inintelligibles &agrave; qui ne les consid&egrave;re pas comme ce qu&apos;au fait ils furent: des auteurs n&eacute;o-latins. <br><font color="green">[But that is not the real question; do we or don&apos;t we have to know our language, vocabulary, syntax, even <mark>semantic</mark>, from the inside, with the help of Latin, and by continually going back to a dark past? The bold author had dared to claim that Racine and Montaigne are surely unintelligible for those who do not see them as what they really were: <mark>neo-Latin writers</mark>.]</font> <small> Jacques Boulenger &amp; Andr&eacute; Th&eacute;rive, <a name="SOIR" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#SOIR"><cite title="source">Les Soir&eacute;es du Grammaire-Club</cite></a> (1924) 156</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
